On Tue, 10 May 2005, Greg Thompson wrote:

> I'm now desparate.  I will gladly pay someone 5$
> (five) U.S. American dollars if they have a 76-79
> automatic bus and will take a picture of the linkage
> at the transmission where the accelerator cable
> connects and email the picture to me.  there is a
> bracket thingy that the flexible tube fits in and the
> the cable exits the flexible tube and connects to the
> relay arm (for the lack of a better term) which then
> connects to a rod that runs into the engine
> compartment and connects to the throttle body.  I need
> a picture of the bracket that bolts to the front of
> the transmission that the rear of the flexible tube
> rests in.  When I move my accelerator linkage at the
> transmission from underneath the bus, I only have
> about 1" of movement with the arm disconnected from
> the throttle body. When I disconnect the accelerator
> cable from the relay arm, I get 2-3 inches of movement
> on the arm and can hear the kickdown click inside the
> transmission.  The kickdown used to work but I think
> the shop that reinstalled the engine after replacing
> the torque converter seal left a piece off at the
> accelerator linkage.  Many, Many thanks!  Greg

there is a really good drawing in the Bentley in the Fuel Injection
chapter,   (10) page 30 fig 6-7

hope this is some help

